revision.text:
The possession and use of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] is illegal in [[El Salvador]] for both [[Recreational drug use|recreational]] and [[medical cannabis|medical]] purposes.<ref name="LaPrensaGrafica2017"/> The country is a signatory of the 1988 [[United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances]], and has criminalized the production and distribution of the drug.{{sfn|Mendiburo-Seguel|Vargas|Oyanedel|Torres|2017|p=8-9}}

El Salvador (along with [[Peru]] and [[Bolivia]]) is one of the most conservative countries in [[Latin America]] in regard to [[drug policy]].{{sfn|Mendiburo-Seguel|Vargas|Oyanedel|Torres|2017|p=8}} According to a 2016 study published by the ''[[International Journal of Drug Policy]]'', only 17% of Salvadorans reported having used cannabis.{{sfn|Mendiburo-Seguel|Vargas|Oyanedel|Torres|2017|p=8}}

==Decriminalization efforts==

In 2014, over 700 people protested in [[San Salvador]] in favor of decriminalizing the consumption and personal cultivation of [[cannabis]]. The demonstration was organized by the [[Activism|activist]] group La María Guanaca and backed by the Evangelical Protestant Church of El Salvador.<ref name="ElNuevoDiario2014"/> 

However, support for cannabis reform remains very low. A 2014 survey by [[Latin_American_Public_Opinion_Project#The_AmericasBarometer|AmericasBarometer]] found that a mere 8% of Salvadorans supported legalization of the drug.{{sfn|Cruz|Queirolo|Boidi|2016|p=7}} According to the survey, support was highest among people with higher levels of education, and low among people who consider religion to be especially important in their lives.{{sfn|Cruz|Queirolo|Boidi|2016|p=7}}

