{{Infobox person | name = Guillermo Rawson | image = GuillermoRawson.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1821|06|24|df=y}} | birth_place = [[San Juan, Argentina]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1890|01|20|1821|06|24|df=y}} | death_place = [[Paris]], France | nationality = Argentine | other_names = | known_for = Interior Minister of Argentina | occupation = Doctor }} Dr. '''Guillermo Rawson''' (24 June 1821 - 20 January 1890) was a medical doctor and politician in nineteenth-century [[Argentina]]. As Interior Minister in 1862 he met Captain [[Sir Love Jones-Parry, 1st Baronet|Love Jones-Parry]] and [[Lewis Jones (Patagonia)|Lewis Jones]] who were on their way to Patagonia to investigate whether it was suitable for the creation of a [[Welsh settlement in Argentina|Welsh settlement]] there. Rawson came to an agreement with them, and this resulted in the creation of a colony in the [[Chubut Valley]] in the following years. The city of [[Rawson, Chubut|Rawson]], the capital of the province of [[Chubut Province|Chubut]] was named after him.
==Biography== [[Image:Buenos Aires - Monumento Guillermo Rawson.jpg|thumb|[[Landmarks in Buenos Aires#Monumento a Guillermo Rawson|Memorial to Guillermo Rawson]] in Buenos Aires.]]
Guillermo Rawson's parents were Dr. [[Aman Rawson]], a doctor who had emigrated from the [[United States]] to Argentina, and Justina Rojo, a daughter of a wealthy family in [[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]], where Guillermo was born. His elder brother was the artist [[Franklin Rawson]]. After a [[Jesuit]] education in San Juan, Rawson graduated from the Medical Faculty of [[University of Buenos Aires]] in 1844. Rawson became interested in politics and democracy. In 1853 he was jailed for opposing [[Nazario Benavidez]], the ''[[caudillo]]'' or ''de facto'' governor of San Juan. The following year he was a member of the [[Paraná Congress]], and from 1862 he was Interior Minister in the government of [[Bartolomé Mitre]].
Apart from politics, Rawson was interested in medicine and hygiene. In 1876 he attended the [[Centennial Exposition]] in [[Philadelphia]] to present his work on public health in Buenos Aires, the most developed body of work on the subject at the time. In 1879, he was elected a member of the [[American Antiquarian Society]].<ref>[http://www.americanantiquarian.org/memberlistr American Antiquarian Society Members Directory]</ref>
Rawson spent a year in [[Paris]] in 1881 for medical treatment, before returning to Argentina. He returned to France for further treatment in 1885 and died in Paris in 1890.
The building of the first Medical School in Buenos Aires is named after him (Escuela Dr Guillermo Rawson).
==Further reading== * Aguilar, A. (1971). ''El Dr. Guillermo Rawson''. San Juan, Argentina: Editorial Sanjuanina. {{es icon}} * Larrain, Jacob (1893). [https://books.google.com/books?id=G0kCAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Larrain+Biograf%C3%ADa+del+doctor+Guillermo+Rawson&hl=en&ei=V6usTOX1PMuhnAeUzujdBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Biografía del doctor Guillermo Rawson''.] La Plata: Imp., Lit. y Encuad. de Solá Hnos. Sesé y Ca. {{es icon}} * Rawson, Guillermo, and Alberto B. Martinez (Ed.) (1891). [https://books.google.com/books?id=a04CAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Escritos+y+discursos+del+doctor+Guillermo+Rawson&hl=en&ei=y6qsTIG9Kou1ngenx7zhDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Escritos y discursos del doctor Guillermo Rawson''] (3rd Edition). Buenos Aires: Compañía Sud-Americana de Billetes de Banco. {{es icon}}
