'''Medical respite care''', also referred to as '''recuperative care''',<ref>{{cite web|title=Recuperative Care: Better Care at Lower Costs|url=http://cmtysolutions.org/blog/recuperative-care-better-care-lower-costs|publisher=Community Solutions|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recuperative Care|url=http://www.kent.gov.uk/adult_social_services/leaflets_and_brochures/recuperative_care.aspx|publisher=Kent County Council|accessdate=13 January 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902070038/http://kent.gov.uk/adult_social_services/leaflets_and_brochures/recuperative_care.aspx|archivedate=2 September 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recuperative Care Center|url=http://www.nhfca.org/Recup/Home.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110618044320/http://www.nhfca.org/Recup/Home.aspx|dead-url=yes|archive-date=18 June 2011|publisher=National Health Foundation|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Illumination Foundation Recuperative Care Center|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jHydaN376tc|publisher=Charlenegp|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> is acute and [[Acute care|post-acute medical care]] for [[Homelessness|homeless persons]] who are too ill or frail to recover from a physical illness or injury on the streets but are not ill enough to be in a hospital. Unlike “respite” for caregivers, “medical respite” is short-term residential care that allows homeless individuals the opportunity to rest in a safe environment while accessing medical care and other supportive services. Medical respite programs provide hospitals with an alternative to discharging homeless patients to the streets or to unequipped shelters when patients would otherwise be discharged to their homes for self-care and recuperation.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Health Care for the Homeless Council|url=http://www.nhchc.org/resources/clinical/medical-respite/|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> In addition to providing post-acute care and clinical oversight, medical respite programs seek to improve [[transitional care]] for this population and end the cycle of homelessness by supporting patients in access benefits and housing.

As of 2014, over 70 medical respite programs have been established across the United States and a number are in development. Medical respite programs are housed in a number of different facility types including homeless shelters, motel rooms, nursing facilities, assisted living facilities and stand-alone facilities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Respite Programs in the United States and Canada|url=http://www.nhchc.org/resources/clinical/medical-respite/tool-kit/medical-respite-programs-united-states-canada/|publisher=National Health Care for the Homeless Council|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> The largest facility is based out of Boston, Massachusetts (United States), called the Barbara McIinnis House, which has 104 beds for men and women in need of a safe place to recuperate after leaving a hospital.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Health Care for the Homeless: Specialized Services|url=http://www.bhchp.org/specializedservices.htm|publisher=Boston Health Care for the Homeless Program|accessdate=13 January 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113051144/http://www.bhchp.org/specializedservices.htm|archivedate=13 November 2013|df=}}</ref> The national average length of stay in medical respite programs is 40 days (30 days median).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhchc.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2014-medical-respite-program-directory.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120055306/http://www.nhchc.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2014-medical-respite-program-directory.pdf |archivedate=2015-01-20 |df= }}</ref>

Studies and discussion about medical respite care include works on an individual<ref>{{cite web|title=Homeless Health Care Case Report|url=http://www.nhchc.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/CaseReportRespiteCare1.pdf|publisher=National Health Care for the Homeless Council Clinicians Network|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref>  and program<ref>{{cite web|title=Clinical Recommendations for the Medical Respite Setting|url=http://www.nhchc.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/ClinicalRecsMedRespite.pdf|publisher=National Health Care for the Homeless Council|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> level. A study out of Chicago looking at the impact of medical respite care on future hospitalizations found that patients who accessed medical respite care required fewer hospital stays (3.7 vs. 8.3 days) in the 12-months after program participation than those discharged from the hospital to the street or shelter.<ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 1483848 | pmid=16735635 | doi=10.2105/AJPH.2005.067850 | volume=96 | title=The effects of respite care for homeless patients: a cohort study | year=2006 | journal=Am J Public Health | pages=1278–81 |vauthors=Buchanan D, Doblin B, Sai T, Garcia P }}</ref> Another study out of Boston found similar results with homeless patients requiring 50% fewer hospital readmissions in the 90-days following medical respite program participation than those released to their own care (the street or shelter).<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=19363773 | doi=10.1080/10852350902735734 | volume=37 | title=Post-hospital medical respite care and hospital readmission of homeless persons | pmc=2702998 | year=2009 | journal=J Prev Interv Community | pages=129–42 |vauthors=Kertesz SG, Posner MA, O'Connell JJ, Swain S, Mullins AN, Shwartz M, Ash AS }}</ref>  Medical respite care has been discussed in the American Medical New Ethics Forum.<ref>{{cite news|title=Treating the Homeless can go beyond medical care|url=http://www.amednews.com/article/20090302/profession/303029974/5/#1|accessdate=13 January 2014|newspaper=American Medical News|date=2 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Respite Media Archive|url=http://www.nhchc.org/resources/clinical/medical-respite/tool-kit/medical-respite-media-archive/|publisher=National Health Care for the Homeless|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref>

Medical respite care is listed as a strategy in the [http://usich.gov/opening_doors/ federal plan to prevent and end homelessness].<ref>http://usich.gov/opening_doors/</ref> The [http://innovation.cms.gov/ Center for Medicare and Medicaid Innovation] is currently conducting a national demonstration program to assess the impact of medical respite care. The demonstration is supported by the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] as an effort to improve health outcomes and health care quality while reducing health care spending for this population.<ref>http://innovation.cms.gov/initiatives/Health-Care-Innovation-Awards-Round-Two/Washington.html</ref>

The [http://www.nhchc.org National Health Care for the Homeless Council] maintains a [http://www.nhchc.org/resources/clinical/medical-respite/respite-care-providers-network/ Respite Care Providers' Network] of over 700 providers, consumers, and advocates who seek to improve access to medical respite care for homeless individuals across the country.<ref>http://www.nhchc.org/resources/clinical/medical-respite/respite-care-providers-network/</ref>

