{{Cleanup biography|date=August 2010}}

[[Major-General]] '''Sir Robert McCarrison''', [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]], [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]] (15 March 1878 – 18 May 1960<ref name=McCarrisonObituary28051960>{{citation |date=28 May 1960 |author= |title=Obituary: Sir ROBERT McCARRISON, C.I.E., M.D., D.Sc. L.L.D., F.R.C.P |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1|issue=5186 |pages=1663–1664 |pmc=1967996|pmid=13856887 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.5186.1663}}</ref>) was a [[Northern Ireland]] [[physician]] and [[nutritionist]] in the [[Indian Medical Service]], who was made a Companion of the Indian Empire (CIE) in 1923,<ref name=LondonGazette3946-7>{{citation |date=2 June 1923 |title=Companion of the Indian Empire (C.I.E.) conferred |journal=[[London Gazette|Supplement to the London Gazette]] |issue=No.32830 |page=3947 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/32830/supplements/3947 |accessdate=10 August 2010}} (See p.3946 for list heading)</ref> received a knighthood in July 1933,<ref name=LondonGazette4716>{{citation |date=14 July 1933 |title=Knighthood conferred July 1933 |journal=The London Gazette |issue=No.33960 |page=4716 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/33960/pages/4716 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> and was appointed as Honourable Physician to the King in 1935.<ref name=LondonGazette7671>{{citation |date=3 December 1935 |title=McCarrison appointment as Honourable Physician to the King |journal=The London Gazette |issue=No.34226 |page=7671 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/34226/pages/7671 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref>

McCarrison was born in [[Portadown]], in [[County Armagh]], [[Northern Ireland]]. He qualified in Medicine at [[Queen's College, Belfast]] in 1900. He joined the [[Indian Medical Service]] and was posted as Medical Officer to Indian troops guarding the mountainous Northern Frontiers. He was promoted to Captain in January 1904,<ref name=LondonGazette3356>{{citation |date=24 May 1904 |title=Robert McCarrison: Lieutenant to Captain on 29 January 1904 |journal=The London Gazette |issue=No. 27679  |page=3356 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/27679/pages/3356 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> to Major in July 1912,<ref name=LondonGazette6377>{{citation |date=27 August 1912 |title=Indian Medical Service: Robert McCarrison, MD: Captain to Major on 29 July 1912 |journal=The London Gazette |issue=No. 28639 |page=6377 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/28639/pages/6377 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> Lieutenant-Colonel in January 1918,<ref name=LondonGazette11>{{citation |date=1 January 1918 |title=Maj. R. McCarrison listed for Lieutenant-Colonel |journal=Supplement to the London Gazette |issue=No. 30450 |page=11 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/30450/supplements/11 |accessdate=10 August 2010}} (List heading: "To be Brevet Lieutenant-Colonerl" is on p.10)</ref> Colonel from 1929,<ref name=LondonGazette3657>{{citation |date=5 June 1931 |title=Indian R. McCarrison to be Colonel from 5th November 1929|journal=The London Gazette |issue=No.  33723  |page=3657 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/33723/pages/3657 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> and to Major-General in July 1933.<ref name=LondonGazette1079>{{citation |date=16 February 1934 |title=Indian Medical Service: Col. Sir R. McCarrison, Kt., C.I.E., M.D., F.R.C.P., K.H.P., to be Maj.-Gen., 19th July 1933 |issue=No. 34024 |page=1079 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/34024/pages/1079 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> He retired from the Indian Medical Service on 19 August 1935.<ref name=LondonGazette5536>{{citation |date=30 August 1935 |title=Indian Medical Service: Maj.-Gen. Sir R. McCarrison retires, 19th Aug. 1935 |issue=No. 34194 |page=5536 |url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/34194/supplements/5536 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> McCarrison's research in India on the cause of [[goiter|goitre]] won widespread recognition and in 1913 he was promoted to do research. In 1928 he became Director of Nutritional Research in India, where he remained until his retirement from the Indian Medical Service in 1935, when he returned to [[England]], settling at [[Oxford]].<ref name=McCarrisonObituary28051960/>

==Pioneer in nutrition research==
McCarrison carried out the very first experiments to demonstrate the effect of [[nutrition]] on the [[epidemiology]] of disease.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}

McCarrison is credited with being the first to experimentally demonstrate the effect of deficient dietaries upon animal tissues and organs.<ref name=BMJPMC2314713>{{citation |date=13 June 1931 |title=Surgery and Diet |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1 |issue=3675 |pages=1031–1032|pmc=2314713 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2841.1031-a}}</ref> He also carried out human experiments aimed at identifying the cause of goitre, and included himself as one of the experimental subjects.<ref name=BMJPMC2318200>{{citation |date=13 February 1909 |title=The Etiology of Goitre |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1 |issue=2511 |page=434|pmc=2318200 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2511.427}}</ref> Much of McCarrison's work was pioneering. His 1921 book ''Studies in Deficiency Disease'' was considered notable at the time, being published at a time when knowledge of vitamins and their role in nutrition was crystallizing.<ref name=Halliburton1921>{{citation |date=18 June 1921 |author=Halliburton, W.D |title=Deficiency Disease (book review) |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1 |issue=3155 |pages=896–897|pmc=2415481 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3155.896}}</ref>  McCarrison himself noted that prior to publication of his studies on the pathogenesis of deficiency disease "no systemic ''post-mortem'' examination of animals fed on food deficient in [[vitamin B]] had ever been made; the histopathological effects of such food on the various systems of the body were wholly unknown; above all, its effects on the gastro-intestinal tract and the organs of digestion and assimilation, and the significance of these effects for clinical medicine, were wholly unsuspected".<ref name=McCarrisonPMC2523693>{{citation |date=10 April 1926 |author=McCarrison, R |title=Vitamin Deficiency |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1 |issue=3406 |page=674|pmc=2523693 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3406.674}}</ref>

At age 23, McCarrison went to India, where he spent 30 years on nutritional problems.<ref name=Moore1953>{{citation |date=25 April 1953 |author=Moore, T |title=Nutrition and Health (book review) |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1 |issue=4816 |page=922 |pmc=2016372 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.4816.922}}. Retrieved 12 August 2010</ref> He attained the rank of major-general in the Indian Medical Service,<ref name=LondonGazette1079/> and founded the Nutritional Research Laboratories in [[Coonoor]].<ref name=Moore1953/> After retiring from the Indian Medical Service in 1935,<ref name=LondonGazette5536/> he gave a series of Cantor lectures at the Royal Society of Arts, about the influence of diet on health.<ref name=Moore1953/> This comprised three lectures delivered on successive Mondays at the Society. The first lecture focused on the processes of nutrition; the second, on food essentials and their relationship to bodily structure and function; the third on disease prevention and physique improvement by attention to diet.<ref name=McCarrisonPMC2457947>{{citation |date=29 February 1936 |author=McCarrison, Sir Robert |title=Nutrition and National Health |series=Cantor Lectures by Sir Robert McCarrison |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=1 |issue=3921 |pages=427–430 |doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3921.427 |url=http://www.bmj.com/cgi/pdf_extract/1/3921/427 |pmc=2457947 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> The lectures were subsequently published in book form under the title ''Nutrition and Health'', and at the time of the third edition in 1962, were still not seen as "dated", with the advances of the preceding 25 years largely filling the details of the principles previously recognised by McCarrison.<ref name=Widdowson1963>{{citation |date=January 1963 |author=Widdowson, E.M |title=Nutrition and Health, being the Cantor Lectures delivered before The Royal Society of Arts, together with Two Earlier Essays (book review) |journal=British Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=20 |issue=1 |page=69|pmc=1038277 |doi=10.1136/oem.20.1.69}}</ref>

"McCarrison's work on goitre, [[cretinism]], and  [[thyroid]], begun in the western Himalayas in 1902, generated scores of scientific publications during the following thirty-five years",<ref name=Miles1998>{{citation |year=1998 |author=Miles, M |title=Goitre, cretinism and iodine in South Asia: historical perspectives on a continuing scourge |journal=Medical History |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=47–67|pmc=1043968 |pmid=9536623 |doi=10.1017/s002572730006333x}}</ref> While McCarrison's work is often considered the start of serious studies of goitre and cretinism in [[South Asia]], it was preceded by that of Commissioner [[David Scott]] at Rangur in north-east India around 1825, and was investigated by Mountford Bramley at [[Kathmandu]] in 1832.<ref name=Miles1998/>

In 1918, McCarrison founded the ''Beri-Beri Enquiry Unit'' in a single room laboratory at the [[Pasteur Institute]] in Conoor, India.<ref name=NINorigins/> He was invalided to Britain from 1920–1922, and in 1923 the enquiry was axed on financial grounds. It was restored two years later as the ''Deficiency Disease Inquiry'', which McCarrison headed from 1925-1929.<ref name=Arnold2000>{{citation |year=2000 |author=Arnold, David |title=Science, technology, and medicine in Colonial India |series=[[The New Cambridge History of India]]. Part III, Volume 5 |pages=201, 215 |place=Cambridge, UK |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-56319-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7bAxnPwOMd8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=science+technology+india#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref> Around 1928-29, this developed further into the Nutrition Research Laboratories (NRL. Renamed the [[National Institute of Nutrition, Hyderabad|National Institute of Nutrition]] in 1969),<ref name=NINorigins/> with McCarrison as its first Director, until his retirement in 1935.<ref name=Moore1953/><ref name=NINorigins>{{citation |title=Down the memory lane |publisher=National Institute of Nutrition, Hyderabad, India |url=http://www.ninindia.org/nin.htm |accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=Arnold2000/> In 1926, as head of the ''Deficiency Diseases Inquiry'', McCarrison submitted written and oral evidence on [[malnutrition]] to the ''Royal Commission on Agriculture in India''.<ref name=McCarrison1928RoyalComm>{{citation |year=1928 |author=McCarrison, Lieut.-Colonel R|chapter=Memorandum on Malnutrition as a cause of physical inefficiency and ill-health among the masses in India (pp.96-98); Oral evidence (pp.99-116) | chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/evidenceofoffice031789mbp#page/n118/mode/1up |series=Evidence of Officers serving under the Government of India |title=Royal Commission on Agriculture in India. Volume I, Part II |place=Calcutta |publisher=Government of India, Central Publication Branch |pages=95–116 (n118–n139 in electronic page fields) |url=https://archive.org/stream/evidenceofoffice031789mbp#page/n5/mode/2up |accessdate=12 August 2010}} (Full text at Internet Archive</ref> The primary objective of McCarrison's submission was to indicate the significance of malnutrition "as a cause of physical inefficiency and ill-health among the massess in India"; the relationship between nutrition and agriculture; and "the necessity for closer co-ordination of nutritional, medical, veterinary and agricultural research" in India.<ref name=McCarrison1928RoyalCommp95>McCarrison, Lieut.-Colonel R (1928), p.95</ref> McCarrison's submission had impact. "A decade later, when the Commission's chairman, [[Victor Hope, 2nd Marquess of Linlithgow|Lord Linlithgow]], became Viceroy of India he showed a personal interest in nutrition, pushing it to the top of the research agenda. In 1936 a Nutrition Advisory Committee was established and roughly a tenth of IRFA's annual grants went to fund nutrition research at Coonoor and [[Calcutta]]".<ref name=Arnold2000/>

==Retirement from India==
After [[the Second World War]], from 1945 to 1955, McCarrison served  as director of postgraduate [[medical education]] at [[Oxford University]].<ref name=McCarrisonObituary28051960/>

==Personal life==
In 1906 he married Helen Stella Johnston, to whom he was still married at the time of his death.<ref name=McCarrisonObituary28051960/>

==Legacy==
* The National Institute of Nutrition in [[Hyderabad]], India, continues to pay tribute to is origins in 1928 under McCarrison.<ref name=NINorigins/>
* McCarrison is grouped, along with [[Albert Howard|Sir Albert Howard]] and [[Richard St. Barbe Baker]], as one of three progenitors of the [[Organic farming|organic agriculture]] movement.<ref name=Mantle>{{citation |author=Mantle, Paul |title=Two Reviews (see review of ''Origins of the Organic Movement'') |work=Tributes |page=7 |publisher=The Man of the Trees: Richard St. Barbe Baker |url=http://www.manofthetrees.org/HTMLS/reviews.htm |accessdate=14 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108223659/http://www.manofthetrees.org/HTMLS/reviews.htm |archivedate=8 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Sayre>{{citation |date=4 March 2004 |author=Sayre, Laura |title=Review: ''The Origins of the Organic Movement'' |publisher=[[The Rodale Institute|Rodale Institute]] |url=http://newfarm.rodaleinstitute.org/books/reviews/march04/origins.shtml |accessdate=14 August 2010}}</ref>

===McCarrison Society===
In 1966, a group of doctors, dentists and veterinarians, interested in the promotion of nutrition and health, founded the McCarrison Society in honour of his efforts,<ref name=Ferry1983>{{citation |date=6 October 1983 |author=Ferry, Georgina |title=Eat your way to mental health |journal=[[New Scientist]] |volume=100 |issue=1378 |page=46 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F0aIiC-z5_kC&pg=PA46&dq=%22eat+your+way+to+mental+health%22#v=onepage&q=%22eat%20your%20way%20to%20mental%20health%22&f=false |accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=McCarrisonSociety/> with a [[Scotland|Scottish]] group established in 1981 due to both travel logistics and differing needs in the Scottish population.<ref name=McCarrisonSociety/>

The Society aims "to assemble scientific knowledge on nutrition and health that is free from economic and political pressures with the object of securing the physical and mental health of future generations".<ref name=McCarrisonSociety>{{citation |title=The McCarrison Society (Scottish Group) |url=http://www.foodforhealthscotland.org/McCarrison%20Society%20Scottish%20Group%20flyer%201.pdf |accessdate=13 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726061343/http://www.foodforhealthscotland.org/McCarrison%20Society%20Scottish%20Group%20flyer%201.pdf |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Society meetings sometimes raise questions with elusive answers, with speakers presenting material based on scanty, often anectdotal data, inviting criticism that it is "a gathering of cranks". However, "one answer to that criticism is that speakers at MCarrison meetings tend to be rather well qualified. But the main point is that the society has a way of asking questions about the environment - what are we doing to it and what it is doing to us - that are of profound importance".<ref name=NewScientisteditorial>{{citation |date=6 October 1983 |author=Editorial |title=Big questions with elusive answers |journal=New Scientist |volume=100 |issue=1378 |page=2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F0aIiC-z5_kC&pg=PA2&dq=%22big+questions%22+elusive#v=onepage&q=%22big%20questions%22%20elusive&f=false |accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref>

The Society's website summarises McCarrison's work thus:
<blockquote>
His researches were extensive; they included work on the newly discovered [[vitamins]] and on the contrasting disease patterns in the [[Indian subcontinent]]. He demonstrated how many common diseases increasingly prevalent in industrial societies were caused simply by diets made defective by extensive food processing, often with the use of chemical additives. He deplored the universal consumption in Britain and America of refined white flour, instead of [[halite flour]], and the substitution of canned, preserved and artificially sweetened products for fresh natural food.
<br/>
McCarrison's work was widely published in the medical press. He was honoured for his discoveries, but completely ignored by government and the medical profession at a time when medical thought was absorbed in the study of disease rather than on prevention and the promotion of health.<ref name=McCarrisonSummary>{{citation |title=Sir Robert McCarrison |publisher=McCarrison Society for Nutrition and Health |url=http://www.mccarrisonsociety.org.uk/founders-of-nutrition-othermenu-149/134-sir-robert-mccarrison |accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref></blockquote>

