{{Infobox medical condition (new) | synonyms = Robinow-like syndrome | name = Saal Greenstein syndrome | image = Autosomal recessive - en.svg | image_size = 140px | alt = | caption = Autosomal recessive is the manner of inheritance of this condition | pronounce = | field = | geneReviewsID = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''Saal Greenstein syndrome''' is a very rare autosomal recessive genetic disorder characterized by stunted growth, short limbs, [[microcephaly]], and an anomalous cleavage of the [[Anterior chamber of eyeball|anterior chamber of the eye]]. The disorder is similar to [[Robinow syndrome]] except for [[anterior chamber]] anomalies and, in one case, [[hydrocephalus]].<ref>{{cite journal| title=Autosomal recessive Robinow-like syndrome with anterior chamber cleavage anomalies.| last1=Greenstein| first1=R.M.| last2=Weinbaum| first2=P.J.| last3=Poole| first3=A.E.| journal=American Journal of Medical Genetics|date=July 1988| volume=30| issue=3| pages=709–718| doi=10.1002/ajmg.1320300303| pmid=3189394}}</ref>
